GM gets new pickup trucks back in the U.S. to repair the seat back
General Motors call almost 19,000 of its brand new Chevrolet Silverado and GMC Sierra pickup trucks with Year 2014 back to fix a problem with the manually adjustable seat back, read a statement from the U.S. regulatory authority for vehicle safety on Friday.
Some of the car, there may be a defect in the mechanism for resetting the front seat back.
For this reason they do not meet the federal guidelines for vehicle safety with head restraints.
"If it is ascended from behind the vehicle, it is possible that the head restraint, the occupant does not protect properly, so an increased risk of injury" was to read the message on the website of the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA).
The recalled models were between 1 August and 10 September produced.
The delivery of the GM trucks began in June and is the most important model launch of the leading U.S. automaker since its 2009 bankruptcy related restructuring dar.
GM informed the vehicle owner in the first half of October over the defect.
The NHTSA was because of the 16-day government shutdown does not consider what a negative impact on car sales in October, the notification letter.
The sale of the Silverado and Sierra trucks that have been redesigned for model year 2014 had increased by 20 percent in the first ten months of the year, GM said on Friday.
In October, GM sold 42 660 Silverado and 16,503 Sierra pickup trucks.
The GM shares rose on the New York Stock Exchange by 1.4 percent to 37.47 U.S. dollars on Friday afternoon.
